# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ship-breaking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] Able UK is a British industrial services company, operating primarily in the marine decommissioning and recycling business.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] The company also undertakes general demolition work.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] The company has non-port sites at or near (as of 2014): Barnby Dun (the former Thorpe Marsh Power Station); and at Seaton (*Seaton Meadows* landfill site).
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] As of 2014 Able UK is also promoting and planning two sites in the north of Lincolnshire, near the banks of the Humber Estuary.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] The "ABLE Humber Port" consists of "ABLE Logistics Park" is a logistic park of nearly 500 hectares (1,200 acres), with an adjacent port development "ABLE Marine Energy Park" of over 360 hectares (890 acres) with nearly 1,400 metres (4,600 ft) of quay on the banks of the Humber Estuary.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] ABLE Logistics Park received planning permission in 2013.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] ABLE Marine Energy Park received local planning permission in 2013, and sought a Development Consent Order in 2014; a planning decision was delayed due to objections from ABP, which were judicially rejected in 2015.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] Able UK was founded in 1966 by Peter Stephenson.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] In 1995 Able acquired the land of the closed Thorpe Marsh Power Station.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] In 1996 Able acquired the dock at Graythorp, renaming it the TERRC (*Teesside Environmental Reclamation and Recycling Centre*) together with the nearby Seaton Meadows landfill site.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] In 2000 Able acquired a fabrication facility in Middlesbrough (formerly *Davy Offshore Modules*, later *SLP Engineering*, and *Odebrecht*.) renaming it *Able Middlesbrough Port*.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] In 2003 the TERRC facility became the subject of controversy when Able obtained a £11 million contract from the United States Maritime Administration to dismantle 13 former US navy ships (known as the *Ghost Ships*).
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] Due to the presence of asbestos and polychlorinated biphenyls in the ships the action was opposed by some Hartlepool residents and environmental groups.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] Able acquired a license to carry out the work from the Environment Agency in 2008.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] The delays caused by the objections to the process caused Able to lose the US contract for 9 of the 13 ships.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] In 2007 Able was fined £20,000 for failing to follow proper procedures when disposing of asbestos.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] By 2009 the four US ships that had been received at the site, together with the former French aircraft carrier *Clemenceau*, were sealed inside the dry dock, which was drained, and the ships scrapped.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] Other constructions decommissioned at the same time included the former jacket of an installation from the North West Hutton Oilfield.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] The TERRC site was again the subject of a planning conflict in 2012 when Hartlepool Borough Council rejected a planning submission (to extend the height Seaton Meadows landfill) made in an attempt to prevent spontaneous combustion of refuse which had been occurring.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] In 2014 proceedings for a *Development Consent Order* for the AMEP plan were begun.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] ABP was subsequently accused of filing wrecking amendments at the initial hearings.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] ABP sought a modification of the plans, shortening the AMEP quay by 515 metres (1,690 ft).
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] At hearings in April 2014 ABP's petitions of objections were found to be valid, requiring the development case to be heard by a committee of MPs.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] By July 2014 other issues with the plan had been withdrawn, with the ABP petitions to be heard at an inquiry in October.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] In August 2014 work began on a £60 million environmental remediation scheme for AMEP to create an alternative wading bird habitats on the banks of the Humber, enabling works began for the AMEP development in the same month, with £15 million funding coming from a government grant.
[src:ship-breaking/able-uk] In October 2014 the parliamentary committee rejected ABP's petitions, and in February 2015 ABP ended its legal opposition to the plans following rejection of a judicial review of the planning decision.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Nonpoint source pollution includes sediment runoff, nutrient runoff and pesticides.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Point source pollution includes animal wastes, silage liquor, milking parlour (dairy farming) wastes, slaughtering waste, vegetable washing water and firewater.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Many farms generate nonpoint source pollution from surface runoff which is not controlled through a treatment plant.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Farmers can install erosion controls to reduce runoff flows and retain soil on their fields.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Common techniques include contour plowing, crop mulching, crop rotation, planting perennial crops and installing riparian buffers.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Farmers can also develop and implement nutrient management plans to reduce excess application of nutrients and reduce the potential for nutrient pollution.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] To minimize pesticide impacts, farmers may use Integrated Pest Management (IPM) techniques (which can include biological pest control) to maintain control over pests, reduce reliance on chemical pesticides, and protect water quality.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Nonpoint source pollution from farms is caused by surface runoff from fields during rain storms.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Agricultural runoff is a major source of pollution, in some cases the only source, in many watersheds.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Soil washed off fields is the largest source of agricultural pollution in the United States.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Excess sediment causes high levels of turbidity in water bodies, which can inhibit growth of aquatic plants, clog fish gills and smother animal larvae.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Farmers may utilize erosion controls to reduce runoff flows and retain soil on their fields.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Nitrogen and phosphorus are key pollutants found in runoff, and they are applied to farmland in several ways, such as in the form of commercial fertilizer, animal manure, or municipal or industrial wastewater (effluent) or sludge.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] These chemicals may also enter runoff from crop residues, irrigation water, wildlife, and atmospheric deposition.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Pesticides are widely used by farmers to control plant pests and enhance production, but chemical pesticides can also cause water quality problems.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Some pesticides have also been detected in groundwater.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Farmers may use Integrated Pest Management (IPM) techniques (which can include biological pest control) to maintain control over pests, reduce reliance on chemical pesticides, and protect water quality.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] There are few safe ways of disposing of pesticide surpluses other than through containment in well managed landfills or by incineration.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] In some parts of the world, spraying on land is a permitted method of disposal.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Farms with large livestock and poultry operations, such as factory farms, can be a major source of point source wastewater.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] In the United States, these facilities are called concentrated animal feeding operations or *confined animal feeding operations* and are being subject to increasing government regulation.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been found to infiltrate the water cycle from farms.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Raising animals accounts for 73% of antibiotics use globally, and wastewater treatment facilities can transfer antibiotic-resistant bacteria to humans.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Animal wastes from cattle can be produced as solid or semisolid manure or as a liquid slurry.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The production of slurry is especially common in housed dairy cattle.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Whilst solid manure heaps outdoors can give rise to polluting wastewaters from runoff, this type of waste is usually relatively easy to treat by containment and/or covering of the heap.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Animal slurries require special handling and are usually treated by containment in lagoons before disposal by spray or trickle application to grassland.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Constructed wetlands are sometimes used to facilitate treatment of animal wastes, as are anaerobic lagoons.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Excessive application or application to sodden land or insufficient land area can result in direct runoff to watercourses, with the potential for causing severe pollution.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Application of slurries to land overlying aquifers can result in direct contamination or, more commonly, elevation of nitrogen levels as nitrite or nitrate.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The disposal of any wastewater containing animal waste upstream of a drinking water intake can pose serious health problems to those drinking the water because of the highly resistant spores present in many animals that are capable of causing disabling disease in humans.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] This risk exists even for very low-level seepage via shallow surface drains or from rainfall run-off.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Some animal slurries are treated by mixing with straws and composted at high temperature to produce a bacteriologically sterile and friable manure for soil improvement.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Piggery waste is comparable to other animal wastes and is processed as for general animal waste, except that many piggery wastes contain elevated levels of copper that can be toxic in the natural environment.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The liquid fraction of the waste is frequently separated off and re-used in the piggery to avoid the prohibitively expensive costs of disposing of copper-rich liquid.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Ascarid worms and their eggs are also common in piggery waste and can infect humans if wastewater treatment is ineffective.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Fresh or wilted grass or other green crops can be made into a semi-fermented product called silage which can be stored and used as winter forage for cattle and sheep.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The production of silage often involves the use of an acid conditioner such as sulfuric acid or formic acid.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The process of silage making frequently produces a yellow-brown strongly smelling liquid which is very rich in simple sugars, alcohol, short-chain organic acids and silage conditioner.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] This liquor is one of the most polluting organic substances known.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The volume of silage liquor produced is generally in proportion to the moisture content of the ensiled material.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Silage liquor is best treated through prevention by wilting crops well before silage making.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Any silage liquor that is produced can be used as part of the food for pigs.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The most effective treatment is by containment in a slurry lagoon and by subsequent spreading on land following substantial dilution with slurry.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Containment of silage liquor on its own can cause structural problems in concrete pits because of the acidic nature of silage liquor.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Although milk is an important food product, its presence in wastewaters is highly polluting because of its organic strength, which can lead to very rapid de-oxygenation of receiving waters.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Milking parlour wastes also contain large volumes of wash-down water, some animal waste together with cleaning and disinfection chemicals.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Milking parlour wastes are often treated in admixture with human sewage in a local sewage treatment plant.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] This ensures that disinfectants and cleaning agents are sufficiently diluted and amenable to treatment.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Running milking wastewaters into a farm slurry lagoon is a possible option although this tends to consume lagoon capacity very quickly.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Land spreading is also a treatment option.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Wastewater from slaughtering activities is similar to milking parlour waste (see above) although considerably stronger in its organic composition and therefore potentially much more polluting.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Treatment is as for milking parlour waste.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Washing of vegetables produces large volumes of water contaminated by soil and vegetable pieces.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Low levels of pesticides used to treat the vegetables may also be present together with moderate levels of disinfectants such as chlorine.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Most vegetable washing waters are extensively recycled with the solids removed by settlement and filtration.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The recovered soil can be returned to the land.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Although few farms plan for fires, fires are nevertheless more common on farms than on many other industrial premises.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Stores of pesticides, herbicides, fuel oil for farm machinery and fertilizers can all help promote fire and can all be present in environmentally lethal quantities in firewater from fire fighting at farms.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] All farm environmental management plans should allow for containment of substantial quantities of firewater and for its subsequent recovery and disposal by specialist disposal companies.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] The concentration and mixture of contaminants in firewater make them unsuited to any treatment method available on the farm.
[src:ship-breaking/agricultural-wastewater-treatment] Even land spreading has produced severe taste and odour problems for downstream water supply companies in the past.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] The **Alang Ship Breaking Yard** is the world's largest ship breaking yard, responsible for dismantling more than a third of retired freight and cargo ships salvaged from around the world.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] It is located on the Gulf of Khambhat by the town of Alang, in the district of Bhavnagar in the state of Gujarat, India.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] Sundaresan was the founder of Alang Ship Recycling Yard in 1983, the shipyard is believed to have acquired a total of US$110.6 billion in aggregate value, including total assets.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] Its growth has prompted its extension northeast towards Sosiya in Gujarat, and it is now often referred to as the Alang-Sosiya Yard.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] The Alang facility consists of 183 ship breaking yards along 14 kilometres (8.7 mi) of coast that total 4.5 million light displacement tonnage (LDT) of capacity.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] Large super-tankers, car ferries, container ships and ocean liners are beached on the mud flats during high tide.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] As the tide recedes, manual labourers move onto the beach to dismantle each ship, salvaging what they can and reducing the rest to scrap.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] The first ship broken down at Alang, MV *Kota Tenjong*, was beached on 13 February 1983.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] Alang's processing peaked between 2011 and 2012 at 415 vessels per year, and has been declining since.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] In 2020, Alang Ship Breaking Yard recycled 196 ships.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] The governments of Japan and Gujarat signed a Memorandum of Understanding in 2010, which focused on technology transfer and financial assistance from Japan to upgrade the yard's operations to meet international standards.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] The project aimed to make Alang the largest International Maritime Organization-compliant ship recycling yard in the world.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] This evolved as part of the Delhi-Mumbai Industrial Corridor, an international industrial development project supported by the governments of India and Japan and carried out as a public-private partnership.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] Improvement efforts started in 2017, with the Japanese International Cooperation Agency providing a soft loan of $76 million and the Gujarati Maritime Board providing $35 million toward improvements.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] In 2004, *Regal V*, famous for a deadly fire in 1990 when she was known as *Scandinavian Star*, was broken up at Alang.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] On 31 December 2005, the French aircraft carrier *Clemenceau* left Toulon to be dismantled in Alang, despite protests about improper disposal and mismanagement of toxic waste at the facility.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] In January 2006, the Supreme Court of India temporarily prohibited the *Clemenceau* from entering the port.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] Attempts to reach a settlement were unsuccessful, and *Clemenceau* was sent to a ship-breaking harbour in Britain instead.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] On 15 January, a court ruling by France's *Conseil d'État* ordered *Clemenceau* to return to French waters.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] Shortly after, Able UK, based at the Graythorp yard near Hartlepool, received a disassembly contract to use accepted practices in scrapping the ship.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] Disassembly began on 18 November 2009 and was completed by the end of 2010.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] In December 2009, the longest ship ever built, *Seawise Giant*, was broken up at Alang.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] In August 2012, *Oriental Nicety*, famous for an oil spill in Prince William sound when she was known as *Exxon Valdez*, was scrapped at Alang.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] The salvage yards at Alang have generated controversies about numerous environmental, health and safety issues, including working conditions, workers' living conditions and environmental impact and frequent accidents and death of workers.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] Between January 2009 and October 2012, at least 54 workers were said to have died in work-related accidents at the Alang shipbreaking yards, according to a local workers union.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] This has attracted concern and scrutiny from the IndustriALL Global Union and the EU.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] The recycling activities pollute the beach and surrounding areas, including the water, with heavy metals.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] Additionally, in the past, the nearest full-service hospital was 50 km (31 miles) away in Bhavnagar.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] In March 2019, the Alang Hospital, a multi-speciality hospital at Alang, was inaugurated by Vijay Rupani, the Chief Minister of Gujarat.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] This hospital was set up by the Gujarat Maritime Board, is operated by the Indian Red Cross Society, and is able to provide immediate medical services.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] Other large facilities on the scale of Alang Ship Breaking Yard include the Aliağa Ship Breaking Yard (Turkey), Chittagong Ship Breaking Yard (Bangladesh) and Gadani ship-breaking yard (Pakistan).
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] In the 1980s, Gadani was the largest ship breaking yard; however, competition from newly established yards such as Alang resulted in a significant reduction in output, with Gadani today producing less than one-fifth of the scrap it produced in the 1980s.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] 2004: *Shipbreakers* is a documentary on the industry in Alang by Michael Kot.
[src:ship-breaking/alang-ship-breaking-yard] 2005: *On the Road to Alang*, by Peter Knego of *Maritime Matters*, is a documentary on passenger ships scrapped at Alang.
[src:ship-breaking/alang] As of the 2001 Indian census, Alang had a population of 18,464.
[src:ship-breaking/alang] Males constitute 82% of the population and females 18%.
[src:ship-breaking/alang] Alang has an average literacy rate of 62%, higher than the national average of 59.5%, with 89% of the males and 11% of females literate.
[src:ship-breaking/alang] Seven percent of the population is under 6 years of age.
[src:ship-breaking/alang] Mithi Virdi (or Viradi) was a proposed site consisting of six nuclear reactors with a total capacity of 6,600 MW about 3 km (2 mi) north of the ship breaking beach.
[src:ship-breaking/alang] The proposed nuclear plant faced heavy opposition from the local population.
[src:ship-breaking/alang] As a result, the plans were cancelled and ultimately relocated to Kovvada, Andhra Pradesh.
[src:ship-breaking/alang] The area around the formerly-proposed plant is known for growing some of the highest-quality kesar mango trees.
[src:ship-breaking/alang] The Alang Ship Breaking Yard is the world's largest ship breaking yard, responsible for dismantling more than a third of retired freight and cargo ships salvaged from around the world.
[src:ship-breaking/aliağa] Aliağa lies in the heart of ancient Aeolia.
[src:ship-breaking/aliağa] The town was named after a member of the influential Karaosmanoğulları ayan family, Karaosmanoğlu Ali Ağa, who owned an estate here.
[src:ship-breaking/aliağa] Before the Greco-Turkish War (1919–1922) the population of the town was mainly Greek.
[src:ship-breaking/aliağa] It was a township in Menemen district in 1937 and became a municipality in 1952.
[src:ship-breaking/aliağa] It finally separated from Menemen and became a district on 21 January 1982.
[src:ship-breaking/aliağa] The remains of the ancient city of Myrina are within the boundaries of the district, located at about fifteen km north of Aliağa centre.
[src:ship-breaking/aliağa] Another ancient site is the yet unexplored Gryneion, near Şakran township on the peninsula, to the south of the center town, also at a distance of 15 km (9 mi).
[src:ship-breaking/aliağa] Visitors also often use the road from Aliağa to visit the remains of Aigai in Yuntdağı in Manisa Province.
[src:ship-breaking/aliağa] In 2021, a monastery and floor mosaic were found here during an illegal excavation.
[src:ship-breaking/aliağa] Archaeologists believe that the monastery was used from the 4th century to the 14th century.
[src:ship-breaking/aliağa] The D.550 roadway runs through the city, between Muğla-Edirne and also to İzmir.
[src:ship-breaking/aliağa] Aliağa is also connected to İzmir by İZBAN, a commuter railway operating around İzmir. İZBAN operates 15 daily trains from Aliağa Railway Station to Alsancak Terminal in İzmir.
[src:ship-breaking/aliağa] ESHOT operates the 834 bus line to İzmir as well.
[src:ship-breaking/aliağa] There are several facilities for dismantling and scrapping ships.
[src:ship-breaking/aliağa] The 2020 COVID-19 pandemic sped up the process of ship recycling because owners of idled cruise ships looked to stem the red ink.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Chemically, aluminium is a post-transition metal in the boron group; as is common for the group, aluminium forms compounds primarily in the +3 oxidation state.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The aluminium cation Al3+ is small and highly charged; as such, it has more polarizing power, and bonds formed by aluminium have a more covalent character.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The strong affinity of aluminium for oxygen leads to the common occurrence of its oxides in nature.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is found on Earth primarily in rocks in the crust, where it is the third-most abundant element after oxygen and silicon, rather than in the mantle, and virtually never as the free metal.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It is obtained industrially by mining bauxite, a sedimentary rock rich in aluminium minerals.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The discovery of aluminium was announced in 1825 by Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was initiated by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville in 1856.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium became much more available to the public with the Hall–Héroult process developed independently by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall in 1886, and the mass production of aluminium led to its extensive use in industry and everyday life.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In 1954, aluminium became the most produced non-ferrous metal, surpassing copper.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In the 21st century, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The standard atomic weight of aluminium is low in comparison with many other metals, giving it the low density responsible for many of its uses.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Despite its prevalence in the environment, no living thing is known to metabolize aluminium salts, but aluminium is well tolerated by plants and animals.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Because of the abundance of these salts, the potential for a biological role for them is of interest, and studies are ongoing.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium metal has an appearance ranging from silvery white to dull gray depending on its surface roughness.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium mirrors provides high reflectivity for light in the ultraviolet, visible (on par with silver), and far infrared regions.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is also good at reflecting solar radiation, although prolonged exposure to sunlight in air can deteriorate the reflectivity of the metal; this may be prevented if aluminium is anodized, which adds a protective layer of oxide on the surface.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The density of aluminium is 2.70 g/cm3, about one-third that of steel, much lower than other commonly encountered metals, making aluminium parts easily identifiable through their lightness.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's low density compared to most other metals arises from the fact that its unit cell size is relatively large in proportion to the number of nucleons.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The only lighter metals are the metals of groups 1 and 2, which, apart from beryllium and magnesium, are too reactive for structural use (and beryllium is very toxic).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is not as strong or stiff as steel, but the low density makes up for this in the aerospace industry and for many other applications where light weight and relatively high strength are crucial.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Pure aluminium is quite soft and lacking in strength.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In most applications, various aluminium alloys are used instead because of their higher strength and hardness.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The yield strength of pure aluminium is 7–11 MPa, while aluminium alloys have yield strengths ranging from 200 MPa to 600 MPa.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is ductile, with a percent elongation of 50–70%, and malleable allowing it to be easily drawn and extruded; it is also easily machined and cast.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is an excellent thermal and electrical conductor, and the amount of aluminium required to match the same amperage in copper weighs only half as much.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is capable of superconductivity, with a superconducting critical temperature of 1.2 kelvin and a critical magnetic field of about 100 gauss (10 milliteslas).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It is paramagnetic and thus essentially unaffected by static magnetic fields.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] However, the high electrical conductivity means that it is strongly affected by alternating magnetic fields through the induction of eddy currents.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] An aluminium atom has 13 electrons with an electron configuration of [Ne] 3s2 3p1, with three electrons beyond a stable noble gas configuration.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Accordingly, the combined first three ionization energies of aluminium are far lower than the fourth ionization energy alone.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Such an electron configuration is shared with the other well-characterized members of its group, boron, gallium, indium, and thallium; it is also expected for nihonium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium can surrender its three outermost electrons in many chemical reactions (see below).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The electronegativity of aluminium is 1.61 on the Pauling scale.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] A free aluminium atom has an atomic radius of 143 pm.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] With the three outermost electrons removed, the radius shrinks to 39 pm for a 4-coordinated atom or 53.5 pm for a 6-coordinated atom.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] At standard temperature and pressure, aluminium atoms (when not affected by atoms of other elements) form a face-centered cubic crystal system bound by metallic bonding provided by atoms' outermost electrons; hence, aluminium (at these conditions) is a metal.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] This crystal system is shared by many other metals, such as lead and copper; the size of a unit cell of aluminium is comparable to that of those other metals.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] This system, however, is not shared by the other members of its group: boron has ionization energies too high to allow metallization, thallium has a hexagonal close-packed structure, and gallium and indium have unusual structures that are not close-packed like those of aluminium and thallium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The few electrons that are available for metallic bonding in aluminium are a probable cause for it being soft with a low melting point and low electrical resistivity.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium has one stable isotope, 27Al, which comprises virtually all of the naturally-occurring element.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] This is common for elements with an odd atomic number.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It is therefore a mononuclidic element for standard atomic weight, which is determined completely by that isotope.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is useful in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), as its single stable isotope (though quadrupolar) has a high NMR sensitivity.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] All other isotopes of aluminium are radioactive.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The most stable of these is 26Al, with a half-life of 717,000 years.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] While it was present along with stable 27Al in the interstellar medium from which the Solar System formed (believed to have been produced by stellar nucleosynthesis also), no detectable amount could have survived the time since the formation of the planet.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] However, minute traces of 26Al are still produced from decay of argon in the atmosphere induced by ionizing radiation of cosmic rays.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The ratio of 26Al to 10Be has been used for the radiodating of geological processes over 105 to 106 year time scales, in particular transport, deposition, sediment storage, burial times, and erosion.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Most meteorite scientists believe that the energy released by the decay of 26Al was responsible for the melting and differentiation of some asteroids after their formation 4.55 billion years ago.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The other known isotopes of aluminium, with mass numbers ranging from 20 to 43, all have half-lives less than 7 minutes, as do the four detected metastable states.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium combines characteristics of pre- and post-transition metals.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Since it has few available electrons for metallic bonding, like the heavier group 13 elements, it has the characteristic physical properties of a post-transition metal, with longer-than-expected interatomic distances.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Furthermore, as Al3+ is a small and highly charged cation, it is strongly polarizing, and bonding in aluminium compounds tends towards covalency; this behavior is similar to that of beryllium (Be2+), displaying an example of a diagonal relationship.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The underlying core of electrons under aluminium's valence shell is that of the preceding noble gas, whereas those of the heavier group 13 elements gallium, indium, thallium, and nihonium also include a filled d-subshell and in some cases a filled f-subshell.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Hence, the inner electrons of aluminium shield the valence electrons almost completely, unlike those of the heavier group 13 elements.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] As such, aluminium is the most electropositive metal in its group, and its hydroxide is in fact more basic than that of gallium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also bears minor similarities to boron (a metalloid), which is in the same group: AlX3 compounds are valence isoelectronic to BX3 compounds (they have the same valence electronic structure), and both behave as Lewis acids and readily form adducts.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Additionally, one of the main motifs of boron chemistry is regular icosahedral structures, and aluminium forms an important part of many icosahedral quasicrystal alloys, including the Al–Zn–Mg class.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium has a high chemical affinity to oxygen, which renders it suitable for use as a reducing agent in the thermite reaction.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] A fine powder of aluminium reacts explosively on contact with liquid oxygen; under normal conditions, however, aluminium forms a thin oxide layer (~5 nm at room temperature) that protects the metal from further corrosion by oxygen, water, or dilute acid, a process termed passivation.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is not attacked by oxidizing acids because of its passivation.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] This allows aluminium to be used to store reagents such as nitric acid, concentrated sulfuric acid, and some organic acids.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In hot, concentrated hydrochloric acid, aluminium reacts with water through evolution of hydrogen, and it reacts in aqueous sodium or potassium hydroxide at room temperature to form aluminates; protective passivation under these conditions is negligible.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is also corroded by dissolved chlorides, such as common sodium chloride.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The oxide layer on aluminium is also destroyed by contact with mercury due to amalgamation or by contact with salts of some electropositive metals.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] As such, the strongest aluminium alloys are less corrosion-resistant due to galvanic reactions with alloyed copper, and aluminium's corrosion resistance is greatly reduced by aqueous salts, particularly in the presence of dissimilar metals.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium reacts with most nonmetals upon heating, forming compounds such as aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), and the aluminium halides (AlX3).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It also forms a wide range of intermetallic compounds involving metals from every group on the periodic table.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The vast majority of aluminium compounds, including all aluminium-containing minerals and all commercially significant aluminium compounds, feature aluminium in the oxidation state 3+.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The coordination number of such compounds varies, but generally Al3+ is either six- or four-coordinate.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Almost all compounds of aluminium(III) are colorless.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In aqueous solution, Al3+ exists as the hexa-aqua cation [Al(H2O)6]3+, which has an approximate Ka of 10−5.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Such solutions are acidic because this cation can act as a proton donor and progressively hydrolyze until a precipitate of aluminium hydroxide, Al(OH)3, forms.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] This is useful for clarification of water, since the precipitate nucleates on suspended particles in the water, hence removing them.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Increasing the pH even further leads to the hydroxide dissolving again as aluminate, [Al(H2O)2(OH)4]−, is formed.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium hydroxide forms both salts and aluminates and dissolves in acid and alkali, as well as on fusion with acidic and basic oxides.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] This behavior of Al(OH)3 is termed amphoterism and is characteristic of weakly basic cations that form insoluble hydroxides and whose hydrated species can also donate their protons.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] One effect of this is that aluminium salts with weak acids are hydrolyzed in water to the aquated hydroxide and the corresponding nonmetal hydride: for example, aluminium sulfide yields hydrogen sulfide.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] However, some salts like aluminium carbonate exist in aqueous solution but are unstable as such.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Only incomplete hydrolysis takes place for salts with strong acids, such as the halides, nitrate, and sulfate.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] For similar reasons, anhydrous aluminium salts cannot be made by heating their "hydrates": hydrated aluminium chloride is in fact not AlCl3·6H2O but [Al(H2O)6]Cl3, and the Al–O bonds are so strong that heating is not sufficient to break them and form Al–Cl bonds.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Unlike the structures of the three heavier trihalides, aluminium fluoride (AlF3) features six-coordinate aluminium, which explains its involatility and insolubility as well as high heat of formation.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Each aluminium atom is surrounded by six fluorine atoms in a distorted octahedral arrangement, with each fluorine atom being shared between the corners of two octahedra.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Such {AlF6} units also exist in complex fluorides such as cryolite, Na3AlF6.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] AlF3 melts at 1,290 °C (2,354 °F) and is made by reaction of aluminium oxide with hydrogen fluoride gas at 700 °C (1,300 °F).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] With heavier halides, the coordination numbers are lower.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The other trihalides are dimeric or polymeric with tetrahedral four-coordinate aluminium centers.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride (AlCl3) has a layered polymeric structure below its melting point of 192.4 °C (378 °F) but transforms on melting to Al2Cl6 dimers.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] At higher temperatures those increasingly dissociate into trigonal planar AlCl3 monomers similar to the structure of BCl3.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium tribromide and aluminium triiodide form Al2X6 dimers in all three phases and hence do not show such significant changes of properties upon phase change.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] These materials are prepared by treating aluminium with the halogen.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The aluminium trihalides form many addition compounds or complexes.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Their Lewis acidic nature makes them useful as catalysts for the Friedel–Crafts reactions.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride has major industrial uses involving this reaction, such as in the manufacture of anthraquinones and styrene.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride is also often used as the precursor for many other aluminium compounds and as a reagent for converting nonmetal fluorides into the corresponding chlorides (a transhalogenation reaction).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium forms one stable oxide with the chemical formula Al2O3, commonly called alumina.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It can be found in nature in the mineral corundum, the α-alumina phase.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Its crystalline form, corundum, is very hard (Mohs hardness 9), has a high melting point of 2,045 °C (3,713 °F), has very low volatility, is chemically inert, and is a good electrical insulator.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It is often used in abrasives (such as sandpaper) as a refractory material and in ceramics.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It is also the starting material for the electrolytic production of aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Sapphire and ruby are impure corundum contaminated with trace amounts of other metals.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The two main oxide-hydroxides, AlO(OH), are boehmite and diaspore.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] There are three main trihydroxides: bayerite, gibbsite, and nordstrandite, which differ in their crystalline structure (polymorphs).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Many other intermediate and related structures are also known.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Most of these Al-O-OH systems are produced from ores by a variety of wet processes using acid and bases.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Heating the hydroxides leads to the formation of corundum.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] These materials are of central importance to the production of aluminium and are themselves extremely useful.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Some mixed oxide phases are also very useful, such as spinel (MgAl2O4), Na-β-alumina (NaAl11O17), and tricalcium aluminate (Ca3Al2O6), an important mineral phase in Portland cement.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The only stable chalcogenides under normal conditions are aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), selenide (Al2Se3), and telluride (Al2Te3).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] All three are prepared by direct reaction of their elements at about 1,000 °C (1,800 °F) and quickly hydrolyze completely in water to yield aluminium hydroxide and the respective hydrogen chalcogenide.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] As aluminium is a small atom relative to these chalcogens, these have four-coordinate tetrahedral aluminium with various polymorphs having structures related to wurtzite, with two-thirds of the possible metal sites occupied either in an orderly (α) or random (β) fashion.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The sulfide also has a γ form related to γ-alumina and an unusual high-temperature hexagonal form where half the aluminium atoms have tetrahedral four-coordination and the other half have trigonal bipyramidal five-coordination.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Four pnictides – aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium phosphide (AlP), aluminium arsenide (AlAs), and aluminium antimonide (AlSb) – are known.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] They are all III-V semiconductors isoelectronic to silicon and germanium, all of which but AlN have the zinc blende structure.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] All four can be made by high-temperature (and possibly high-pressure) direct reaction of their component elements.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium alloys well with most other metals (with the exception of most alkali metals and group 13 metals) and over 150 intermetallics with other metals are known.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Preparation involves heating fixed metals together in certain proportions, followed by gradual cooling and annealing.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Bonding in them is predominantly metallic and the crystal structure primarily depends on efficiency of packing.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] There are few compounds with lower oxidation states.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Some are aluminium(I) compounds: AlF, AlCl, AlBr, and AlI all exist in the gaseous phase when the respective trihalide is heated with aluminium, and at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] A stable derivative of aluminium monoiodide is the cyclic adduct formed with triethylamine, Al4I4(NEt3)4.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Al2O and Al2S also exist but are very unstable.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Very simple aluminium(II) compounds are invoked or observed in the reactions of Al metal with oxidants.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] For example, aluminium monoxide, AlO, has been detected in the gas phase after explosion and in stellar absorption spectra.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] More thoroughly investigated are compounds of the formula R4Al2 which contain an Al–Al bond and where R is a large organic ligand.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] A variety of compounds of empirical formula AlR3 and AlR1.5Cl1.5 exist.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The aluminium trialkyls and triaryls are either reactive, volatile, and colorless liquids or low-melting solids.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] They catch fire spontaneously in air and react with water, thus necessitating precautions when handling them.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] They often form dimers, unlike their boron analogues, but this tendency diminishes for branched-chain alkyls (e.g.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] For example, triisobutylaluminium exists as an equilibrium mixture of the monomer and dimer.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] These dimers, such as trimethylaluminium (Al2Me6), usually feature tetrahedral Al centers formed by dimerization with some alkyl group bridging between both aluminium atoms.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] They are hard acids and react readily with ligands, forming adducts.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In industry, they are mostly used in alkene insertion reactions, as discovered by Karl Ziegler, most importantly in "growth reactions" that form long-chain unbranched primary alkenes and alcohols, and in the low-pressure polymerization of ethene and propene.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] There are also some heterocyclic and cluster organoaluminium compounds involving Al–N bonds.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The industrially most important aluminium hydride is lithium aluminium hydride (LiAlH4), which is used as a reducing agent in organic chemistry.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It can be produced from lithium hydride and aluminium trichloride.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The simplest hydride, aluminium hydride or alane, is not as important.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It is a polymer with the formula (AlH3)*n*, which is in contrast to the corresponding boron hydride that is a dimer with the formula (BH3)2.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's per-particle abundance in the Solar System is 3.15 ppm (parts per million).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It is the twelfth most abundant of all elements and third most abundant among the elements that have odd atomic numbers, after hydrogen and nitrogen.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The only stable isotope of aluminium, 27Al, is the eighteenth most abundant nucleus in the universe.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It is created almost entirely after fusion of carbon in massive stars that will later become Type II supernovas: this fusion creates 26Mg, which upon capturing free protons and neutrons, becomes aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Some smaller quantities of 27Al are created in hydrogen burning shells of evolved stars, where 26Mg can capture free protons.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Essentially all aluminium now in existence is 27Al.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] 26Al was present in the early Solar System with abundance of 0.005% relative to 27Al but its half-life of 728,000 years is too short for any original nuclei to survive; 26Al is therefore extinct.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Unlike for 27Al, hydrogen burning is the primary source of 26Al, with the nuclide emerging after a nucleus of 25Mg catches a free proton.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] However, the trace quantities of 26Al that do exist are the most common gamma ray emitter in the interstellar gas; if the original 26Al were still present, gamma ray maps of the Milky Way would be brighter.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Overall, the Earth is about 1.59% aluminium by mass (seventh in abundance by mass).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium occurs in greater proportion in the Earth's crust than in the universe at large.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] This is because aluminium easily forms the oxide and becomes bound into rocks and stays in the Earth's crust, while less reactive metals sink to the core.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In the Earth's crust, aluminium is the most abundant metallic element (8.23% by mass) and the third most abundant of all elements (after oxygen and silicon).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] A large number of silicates in the Earth's crust contain aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In contrast, the Earth's mantle is only 2.38% aluminium by mass.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also occurs in seawater at a concentration of 0.41 μg/kg.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Because of its strong affinity for oxygen, aluminium is almost never found in the elemental state; instead it is found in oxides or silicates.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Feldspars, the most common group of minerals in the Earth's crust, are aluminosilicates.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also occurs in the minerals beryl, cryolite, garnet, spinel, and turquoise.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Impurities in alumina yield gemstones: for example, chromium yields ruby and iron yields sapphire.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Native aluminium metal is extremely rare and can only be found as a minor phase in low oxygen fugacity environments, such as the interiors of certain volcanoes.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Native aluminium has been reported in cold seeps in the northeastern continental slope of the South China Sea.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It is possible that these deposits resulted from bacterial reduction of tetrahydroxoaluminate Al(OH)4−.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Although aluminium is a common and widespread element, not all aluminium minerals are economically viable sources of the metal.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Almost all metallic aluminium is produced from the ore bauxite (AlO*x*(OH)3–2*x*).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Bauxite occurs as a weathering product of low iron and silica bedrock in tropical climatic conditions.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In 2017, most bauxite was mined in Australia, China, Guinea, and India.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The history of aluminium has been shaped by usage of alum.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The first written record of alum, made by Greek historian Herodotus, dates back to the 5th century BCE.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The ancients are known to have used alum as a dyeing mordant and for city defense as a fire-resistant coating for wood.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] After the Crusades, alum, an indispensable good in the European fabric industry, was a subject of international commerce; it was imported to Europe from the eastern Mediterranean until the mid-15th century.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The nature of alum remained unknown until Swiss physician Paracelsus suggested alum was a salt of an earth of alum around 1530.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] German doctor and chemist Andreas Libavius experimentally confirmed this in 1595.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] German chemist Friedrich Hoffmann announced his belief that the base of alum was a distinct earth in 1722.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] German chemist Andreas Sigismund Marggraf synthesized alumina in 1754 by boiling clay in sulfuric acid and subsequently adding potash.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Attempts to produce aluminium date back to 1760.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The first successful attempt, however, was completed in 1824 by Danish physicist and chemist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] He reacted anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium amalgam, yielding a lump of metal looking similar to tin.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] He presented his results and demonstrated a sample of the new metal in 1825.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In 1827, German chemist Friedrich Wöhler repeated Ørsted's experiments but did not identify any aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] (The reason for this inconsistency was only discovered in 1921.) He conducted a similar experiment in the same year by mixing anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium (the Wöhler process) and produced a powder of aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In 1845, he was able to produce small pieces of the metal and described some physical properties of this metal.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] For many years thereafter, Wöhler was credited as the discoverer of aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] As Wöhler's method could not yield great quantities of aluminium, the metal remained rare; its cost exceeded that of gold.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was established in 1856 by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville and companions.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Sainte-Claire Deville had discovered that aluminium trichloride could be reduced by sodium, which was more convenient and less expensive than potassium, which Wöhler had used.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Even then, aluminium was still not of great purity and produced aluminium differed in properties by sample.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Because of its electricity-conducting capacity, aluminium was used as the cap of the Washington Monument, completed in 1885, the tallest building in the world at the time.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The non-corroding metal cap was intended to serve as a lightning rod peak.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The first industrial large-scale production method was independently developed in 1886 by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall; it is now known as the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The Hall–Héroult process converts alumina into metal.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Austrian chemist Carl Joseph Bayer discovered a way of purifying bauxite to yield alumina, now known as the Bayer process, in 1889.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Modern production of aluminium is based on the Bayer and Hall–Héroult processes.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] As large-scale production caused aluminium prices to drop, the metal became widely used in jewelry, eyeglass frames, optical instruments, tableware, and foil, and other everyday items in the 1890s and early 20th century.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's ability to form hard yet light alloys with other metals provided the metal with many uses at the time.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] During World War I, major governments demanded large shipments of aluminium for light strong airframes; during World War II, demand by major governments for aviation was even higher.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] From the early 20th century to 1980, the aluminium industry was characterized by cartelization, as aluminium firms colluded to keep prices high and stable.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The first aluminium cartel, the Aluminium Association, was founded in 1901 by the Pittsburgh Reduction Company (renamed Alcoa in 1907) and Aluminium Industrie AG.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The British Aluminium Company, Produits Chimiques d'Alais et de la Camargue, and Société Électro-Métallurgique de Froges also joined the cartel.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] By the mid-20th century, aluminium had become a part of everyday life and an essential component of housewares.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In 1954, production of aluminium surpassed that of copper, historically second in production only to iron, making it the most produced non-ferrous metal.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] During the mid-20th century, aluminium emerged as a civil engineering material, with building applications in both basic construction and interior finish work, and increasingly being used in military engineering, for both airplanes and armored vehicle engines.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Earth's first artificial satellite, launched in 1957, consisted of two separate aluminium semi-spheres joined and all subsequent space vehicles have used aluminium to some extent.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The aluminium can was invented in 1956 and employed as a storage for drinks in 1958.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Throughout the 20th century, the production of aluminium rose rapidly: while the world production of aluminium in 1900 was 6,800 metric tons, the annual production first exceeded 100,000 metric tons in 1916; 1,000,000 tons in 1941; 10,000,000 tons in 1971.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In the 1970s, the increased demand for aluminium made it an exchange commodity; it entered the London Metal Exchange, the oldest industrial metal exchange in the world, in 1978.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The output continued to grow: the annual production of aluminium exceeded 50,000,000 metric tons in 2013.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The real price for aluminium declined from $14,000 per metric ton in 1900 to $2,340 in 1948 (in 1998 United States dollars).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Extraction and processing costs were lowered over technological progress and the scale of the economies.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] However, the need to exploit lower-grade poorer quality deposits and the use of fast increasing input costs (above all, energy) increased the net cost of aluminium; the real price began to grow in the 1970s with the rise of energy cost.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Production moved from the industrialized countries to countries where production was cheaper.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Production costs in the late 20th century changed because of advances in technology, lower energy prices, exchange rates of the United States dollar, and alumina prices.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The BRIC countries' combined share in primary production and primary consumption grew substantially in the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] China is accumulating an especially large share of the world's production thanks to an abundance of resources, cheap energy, and governmental stimuli; it also increased its consumption share from 2% in 1972 to 40% in 2010.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In the United States, Western Europe, and Japan, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In 2021, prices for industrial metals such as aluminium have soared to near-record levels as energy shortages in China drive up costs for electricity.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The names *aluminium* and *aluminum* are derived from the word *alumine*, an obsolete term for *alumina*, the primary naturally occurring oxide of aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] *Alumine* was borrowed from French, which in turn derived it from *alumen*, the classical Latin name for alum, the mineral from which it was collected.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The Latin word *alumen* stems from the Proto-Indo-European root **alu-* meaning "bitter" or "beer".
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The English name *alum* does not come directly from Latin, whereas *alumine*/*alumina* comes from the Latin word *alumen* (on declension, *alumen* changes to *alumin-*).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] British chemist Humphry Davy, who performed a number of experiments aimed to isolate the metal, is credited as the person who named the element.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The first name proposed for the metal to be isolated from alum was *alumium*, which Davy suggested in an 1808 article on his electrochemical research, published in Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It appeared that the name was created from the English word *alum* and the Latin suffix *-ium*; but it was customary then to give elements names originating in Latin, so this name was not adopted universally.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The name *alumium* was criticized by contemporary chemists from France, Germany, and Sweden, who insisted the metal should be named for the oxide, alumina, from which it would be isolated.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] One example was *Essai sur la Nomenclature chimique* (July 1811), written in French by a Swedish chemist, Jöns Jacob Berzelius, in which the name *aluminium* is given to the element that would be synthesized from alum.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] (Another article in the same journal issue also refers to the metal whose oxide is the basis of sapphire, i.e., the same metal, as to *aluminium*.) A January 1811 summary of one of Davy's lectures at the Royal Society mentioned the name *aluminium* as a possibility.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In 1812, Davy published his chemistry text *Elements of Chemical Philosophy* in which he used the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In 1812, British scientist Thomas Young wrote an anonymous review of Davy's book, in which he proposed the name *aluminium* instead of *aluminum*, which he thought had a "less classical sound".
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] This name persisted: although the *-um* spelling was occasionally used in Britain, the American scientific language used *-ium* from the start.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The French have used the spelling *aluminium* from the start.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Most scientists throughout the world used *-ium* in the 19th century; and it was entrenched in several other European languages, such as French, German, and Dutch.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In 1828, an American lexicographer, Noah Webster, entered only the *aluminum* spelling in his *American Dictionary of the English Language*.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In the 1830s, the *-um* spelling gained usage in the United States; by the 1860s, it had become the more common spelling there outside science.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In 1892, Hall used the *-um* spelling in his advertising handbill for his new electrolytic method of producing the metal, despite his constant use of the *-ium* spelling in all the patents he filed between 1886 and 1903.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It is unknown whether this spelling was introduced by mistake or intentionally, but Hall preferred *aluminum* since its introduction because it resembled *platinum*, the name of a prestigious metal.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] By 1890, both spellings had been common in the United States, the *-ium* spelling being slightly more common; by 1895, the situation had reversed; by 1900, *aluminum* had become twice as common as *aluminium*; in the next decade, the *-um* spelling dominated American usage.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In 1925, the American Chemical Society adopted the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) adopted *aluminium* as the standard international name for the element in 1990.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In 1993, they recognized *aluminum* as an acceptable variant; the most recent 2005 edition of the IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry also acknowledges this spelling.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] IUPAC official publications use the *-ium* spelling as primary, and they list both where it is appropriate.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Their usage is currently regional: *aluminum* dominates in the United States and Canada; *aluminium* is prevalent in the rest of the English-speaking world.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] German physicist Ludwig Wilhelm Gilbert had proposed *Thonerde-metall*, after the German *Thonerde* for alumina, in his *Annalen der Physik* but that name never caught on at all even in Germany.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Richards in 1891 found just one occurrence of *argillium* in Swedish, from the French *argille* for clay.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The production of aluminium starts with the extraction of bauxite rock from the ground.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The bauxite is processed and transformed using the Bayer process into alumina, which is then processed using the Hall–Héroult process, resulting in the final aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium production is highly energy-consuming, and so the producers tend to locate smelters in places where electric power is both plentiful and inexpensive.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Production of one kilogram of aluminium requires 7 kilograms of oil energy equivalent, as compared to 1.5 kilograms for steel and 2 kilograms for plastic.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] As of 2024, the world's largest producers of aluminium were China, India, Russia, Canada, and the United Arab Emirates, while China is by far the top producer of aluminium with a world share of over 55%.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] According to the International Resource Panel's Metal Stocks in Society report, the global per capita stock of aluminium in use in society (i.e. in cars, buildings, electronics, etc.) is 80 kg (180 lb).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Much of this is in more-developed countries (350–500 kg (770–1,100 lb) per capita) rather than less-developed countries (35 kg (77 lb) per capita).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Bauxite is converted to alumina by the Bayer process.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Bauxite is blended for uniform composition and then is ground fine.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] After this reaction, the slurry is at a temperature above its atmospheric boiling point.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It is cooled by removing steam as pressure is reduced.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The bauxite residue is separated from the solution and discarded.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The solution, free of solids, is seeded with small crystals of aluminium hydroxide; this causes decomposition of the [Al(OH)4]− ions to aluminium hydroxide.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] After about half of aluminium has precipitated, the mixture is sent to classifiers.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Small crystals of aluminium hydroxide are collected to serve as seeding agents; coarse particles are converted to alumina by heating; the excess solution is removed by evaporation, (if needed) purified, and recycled.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The conversion of alumina to aluminium is achieved by the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] In this energy-intensive process, a solution of alumina in a molten (940 and 970 °C (1,720 and 1,780 °F)) mixture of cryolite (Na3AlF6) with calcium fluoride is electrolyzed to produce metallic aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The liquid aluminium sinks to the bottom of the solution and is tapped off, and usually cast into large blocks called aluminium billets for further processing.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Anodes of the electrolysis cell are made of carbon—the most resistant material against fluoride corrosion—and either bake at the process or are prebaked.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The former, also called Söderberg anodes, are less power-efficient and fumes released during baking are costly to collect, which is why they are being replaced by prebaked anodes even though they save the power, energy, and labor to prebake the cathodes.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Carbon for anodes should be preferably pure so that neither aluminium nor the electrolyte is contaminated with ash.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Despite carbon's resistivity against corrosion, it is still consumed at a rate of 0.4–0.5 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Cathodes are made of anthracite; high purity for them is not required because impurities leach only very slowly.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The cathode is consumed at a rate of 0.02–0.04 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] A cell is usually terminated after 2–6 years following a failure of the cathode.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The Hall–Heroult process produces aluminium with a purity of above 99%.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Further purification can be done by the Hoopes process.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] This process involves the electrolysis of molten aluminium with a sodium, barium, and aluminium fluoride electrolyte.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The resulting aluminium has a purity of 99.99%.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Electric power represents about 20 to 40% of the cost of producing aluminium, depending on the location of the smelter.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium production consumes roughly 5% of electricity generated in the United States.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Because of this, alternatives to the Hall–Héroult process have been researched, but none has turned out to be economically feasible.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Recovery of the metal through recycling has become an important task of the aluminium industry.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Recycling was a low-profile activity until the late 1960s, when the growing use of aluminium beverage cans brought it to public awareness.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Recycling involves melting the scrap, a process that requires only 5% of the energy used to produce aluminium from ore, though a significant part (up to 15% of the input material) is lost as dross (ash-like oxide).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] An aluminium stack melter produces significantly less dross, with values reported below 1%.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] White dross from primary aluminium production and from secondary recycling operations still contains useful quantities of aluminium that can be extracted industrially.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The process produces aluminium billets, together with a highly complex waste material.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It reacts with water, releasing a mixture of gases including, among others, acetylene, hydrogen sulfide and significant amounts of ammonia.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Despite these difficulties, the waste is used as a filler in asphalt and concrete.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Its potential for hydrogen production has also been considered and researched.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The global production of aluminium in 2016 was 58.8 million metric tons.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It exceeded that of any other metal except iron (1,231 million metric tons).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is almost always alloyed, which markedly improves its mechanical properties, especially when tempered.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] For example, the common aluminium foils and beverage cans are alloys of 92% to 99% aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The main alloying agents for both wrought and cast aluminium are copper, zinc, magnesium, manganese, and silicon (e.g., duralumin) with the levels of other metals in a few percent by weight.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is the main substitute to copper and its applications to the traditional domains of copper have seen increased interest when copper prices are high such as in 2011–2014 and 2021.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] There is a competition in the use of aluminium and copper in the automotive industry, but in other uses such as in the construction industry and in underground and submarine cables aluminium has been largely unable to compete with copper.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The great majority (about 90%) of aluminium oxide is converted to metallic aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Being a very hard material (Mohs hardness 9), alumina is widely used as an abrasive; being extraordinarily chemically inert, it is useful in highly reactive environments such as high pressure sodium lamps.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium oxide is commonly used as a catalyst for industrial processes; e.g. the Claus process to convert hydrogen sulfide to sulfur in refineries and to alkylate amines.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Many industrial catalysts are supported by alumina, meaning that the expensive catalyst material is dispersed over a surface of the inert alumina.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Another principal use is as a drying agent or absorbent.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Several sulfates of aluminium have industrial and commercial application.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium sulfate (in its hydrate form) is produced on the annual scale of several millions of metric tons.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] About two-thirds is consumed in water treatment.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] The next major application is in the manufacture of paper.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] It is also used as a mordant in dyeing, in pickling seeds, deodorizing of mineral oils, in leather tanning, and in production of other aluminium compounds.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Two kinds of alum, ammonium alum and potassium alum, were formerly used as mordants and in leather tanning, but their use has significantly declined following availability of high-purity aluminium sulfate.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Anhydrous aluminium chloride is used as a catalyst in chemical and petrochemical industries, the dyeing industry, and in synthesis of various inorganic and organic compounds.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Aluminium hydroxychlorides are used in purifying water, in the paper industry, and as antiperspirants.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p01] Sodium aluminate is used in treating water and as an accelerator of solidification of cement.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Despite its widespread occurrence in the Earth's crust, aluminium has no known function in biology.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] At pH 6–9 (relevant for most natural waters), aluminium precipitates out of water as the hydroxide and is hence not available; most elements behaving this way have no biological role or are toxic.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Aluminium sulfate has an LD50 of 6207 mg/kg (oral, mouse).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Aluminium is classified as a non-carcinogen by the United States Department of Health and Human Services.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] A review published in 1988 said that there was little evidence that normal exposure to aluminium presents a risk to healthy adult, and a 2014 multi-element toxicology review was unable to find deleterious effects of aluminium consumed in amounts not greater than 40 mg/day per kg of body mass.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Most ingested aluminium is eliminated in feces, and much of what enters the bloodstream is excreted in urine; however, not all absorbed or parenterally administered aluminium is cleared through urinary excretion.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Aluminium, although rarely, can cause vitamin D-resistant osteomalacia, erythropoietin-resistant microcytic anemia, and central nervous system alterations.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] People with kidney insufficiency are especially at a risk.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Chronic ingestion of hydrated aluminium silicates (for excess gastric acidity control) may result in aluminium binding to intestinal contents and increased elimination of other metals, such as iron or zinc; sufficiently high doses (>50 g/day) can cause anemia.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] During the 1988 Camelford water pollution incident, people in Camelford had their drinking water contaminated with aluminium sulfate for several weeks.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] A final report into the incident in 2013 concluded it was unlikely that this had caused long-term health problems.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Aluminium has been suspected of being a possible cause of Alzheimer's disease, but research into this for over 40 years has found, as of 2018, no good evidence of causal effect.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Aluminium increases estrogen-related gene expression in human breast cancer cells cultured in the laboratory.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] In very high doses, aluminium is associated with altered function of the blood–brain barrier.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] A small percentage of people have contact allergies to aluminium and experience itchy red rashes, headache, muscle pain, joint pain, poor memory, insomnia, depression, asthma, irritable bowel syndrome, or other symptoms upon contact with products containing aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Exposure to powdered aluminium or aluminium welding fumes can cause pulmonary fibrosis.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Fine aluminium powder can ignite or explode, posing another workplace hazard.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Drinking water contains more aluminium than solid food; however, aluminium in food may be absorbed more than aluminium from water.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Dietary exposure in Europeans averages to 0.2–1.5 mg/kg/week but can be as high as 2.3 mg/kg/week.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Higher exposure levels of aluminium are mostly limited to plumbers, masons, electrical workers, machinists, and surgeons.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Consumption of antacids, antiperspirants, vaccines, and cosmetics provide possible routes of exposure.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Consumption of acidic foods or liquids with aluminium enhances aluminium absorption, and maltol has been shown to increase the accumulation of aluminium in nerve and bone tissues.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] In case of suspected sudden intake of a large amount of aluminium, the only treatment is deferoxamine mesylate which may be given to help eliminate aluminium from the body by chelation therapy.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] However, this should be applied with caution as this reduces not only aluminium body levels, but also those of other metals such as copper or iron.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] High levels of aluminium occur near mining sites; small amounts of aluminium are released to the environment at coal-fired power plants or incinerators.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Aluminium in the air is washed out by the rain or normally settles down but small particles of aluminium remain in the air for a long time.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Acidic precipitation is the main natural factor to mobilize aluminium from natural sources and the main reason for the environmental effects of aluminium; however, the main factor of presence of aluminium in salt and freshwater are the industrial processes that also release aluminium into air.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] In water, aluminium acts as a toxic agent on gill-breathing animals such as fish when the water is acidic, in which aluminium may precipitate on gills, which causes loss of plasma- and hemolymph ions leading to osmoregulatory failure.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Organic complexes of aluminium may be easily absorbed and interfere with metabolism in mammals and birds, even though this rarely happens in practice.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Aluminium is primary among the factors that reduce plant growth on acidic soils.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Although it is generally harmless to plant growth in pH-neutral soils, in acid soils the concentration of toxic Al3+ cations increases and disturbs root growth and function.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Wheat has developed a tolerance to aluminium, releasing organic compounds that bind to harmful aluminium cations.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Sorghum is believed to have the same tolerance mechanism.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Aluminium production possesses its own challenges to the environment on each step of the production process.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] The major challenge is the emission of greenhouse gases.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] These gases result from electrical consumption of the smelters and the byproducts of processing.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] The most potent of these gases are perfluorocarbons, namely CF4 and C2F6, from the smelting process.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] Biodegradation of metallic aluminium is extremely rare; most aluminium-corroding organisms do not directly attack or consume the aluminium, but instead produce corrosive wastes.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] The fungus *Geotrichum candidum* can consume the aluminium in compact discs.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-p02] The bacterium *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* and the fungus *Cladosporium resinae* are commonly detected in aircraft fuel tanks that use kerosene-based fuels (not avgas), and laboratory cultures can degrade aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Recycling scrap aluminium requires only 5% of the energy used to make new aluminium from the raw ore.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] In 2022, the United States produced 3.86 metric tons of secondary aluminium for every metric ton of primary aluminium produced.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Over the same time period, secondary aluminium accounted for 34% of the total new supply of aluminium including imports.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Used beverage containers are the largest component of processed aluminium scrap, and most of it is manufactured back into aluminium cans.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] The first step in aluminium recycling is the collection and sorting of aluminium scrap from various sources.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Scrap aluminium comes primarily from either manufacturing scrap or end-of-life aluminium products such as vehicles, building materials, and consumer products.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Manufacturing scrap includes shreds, shavings, cuttings, and other leftover aluminium from manufacturing processes.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Post-consumer scrap consists of obsolete or discarded aluminium products.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Aluminium cans, in particular, are a major source of recyclable aluminium scrap.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Once collected, aluminium scrap is sorted based on alloy type, grade, impurity levels, and other factors.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Sorting may be done manually or using technologies like eddy current separators, air classifiers, and density separators.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] The scrap is sorted into categories like wrought alloy scrap, casting alloy scrap, used beverage cans, automobile scrap, and mixed scrap.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Proper sorting is essential for producing high-quality recycled aluminium.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] After sorting, the scrap may undergo pre-treatment processes to prepare it for melting.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] These can include baling, shredding, crushing, granulating, decoating, and demagnetizing.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Shredding and crushing reduce the particle size of the scrap and liberate it from other materials, while granulating produces fine particles ideal for melting.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Thermal decoating removes coatings like paint and plastic from aluminium surfaces.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Demagnetizing removes iron particles clinging to the aluminium scrap.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Pre-treatment improves the density of the scrap charge and removes contaminants, resulting in faster melting, cleaner metal, reduced dross formation, and lower energy consumption.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Once pre-treated, the aluminium scrap undergoes melting and liquid metal treatment to produce refined aluminium alloy suitable for casting or reprocessing.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Different furnace types are used based on the type of scrap, desired metal quality, and economics.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Smaller scrap is typically processed in rotary or reverberatory gas-fired furnaces, while large individual pieces of scrap can be charged directly into reverb furnaces through side wells.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Electric induction furnaces are also used.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] As the scrap melts, fluxes are added to bind and absorb impurities which are scraped off the top as dross.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Chlorine gas may also be injected to remove impurities through flotation.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] The melt can then undergo refining processes like flux injection to further reduce hydrogen and impurities.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Degassing removes dissolved hydrogen while chemical filtration removes solid impurities and inclusions.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] The final result is molten aluminium alloy ready for casting.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] The molten recycled aluminium is cast into solid forms such as ingots, sows, or directly into sheets or extrusion billets.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Direct-chill casting is commonly used to solidify the liquid aluminium into large cylindrical billets for extrusion or rolling.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] The direct chill method sprays water onto the hot metal as it exits the mold, quickly chilling it into a solid billet form.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] For ingots, book molds are often used, producing slabbed ingots suitable for remelting or rolling.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Continuous casting directly shapes the aluminium into rolling slabs without an intermediate ingot casting step.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Twin-belt or twin-roll strip casting produces alloy strips 6-7mm thick directly from the melt for subsequent rolling.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] The casting method depends on the subsequent processing and use of the recycled aluminium alloy.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Although aluminium in its pure form has been produced as early as 1825, secondary aluminium production, or recycling, rose in volume with the introduction of industrially viable primary aluminium processes, namely the combination of the Bayer and Hall-Héroult processes.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] The Hall-Héroult process for aluminium production from alumina was invented in 1886 by Charles Hall and Paul Héroult.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Carl Josef Bayer created a multi-step process to convert raw bauxite into alumina in 1888.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] As aluminium production rose with the use of these two processes, aluminium recycling grew too.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] In 1904, the first two aluminium can recycling plants were built in the United States; one recycling plant was built in Chicago, Illinois and the other was built in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Aluminium recycling increased most significantly in volume when metal resources were strained during WWI, as the U.S. government campaigned for civilians to donate old products such as aluminium pots, pans, boats, vehicles, and toys to recycle for the construction of aluminium airframes.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Aluminium is an infinitely recyclable material, and it takes up to 95 percent less energy to recycle it than to produce primary aluminium, which also limits emissions, including greenhouse gases.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Today, about 75 percent of all aluminium produced in history, nearly a billion tons, is still in use.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] The recycling of aluminium generally produces significant cost savings over the production of new aluminium, even when the cost of collection, separation and recycling are taken into account.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Over the long term, even larger national savings are made when the reduction in the capital costs associated with landfills, mines, and international shipping of raw aluminium are considered.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Recycling aluminium uses about 5% of the energy required to create aluminium from bauxite; the amount of energy required to convert aluminium oxide into aluminium can be vividly seen when the process is reversed during the combustion of thermite or ammonium perchlorate composite propellant.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Aluminium die extrusion is a specific way of getting reusable material from aluminium scraps but does not require a large energy output of a melting process.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] In 2003, half of the products manufactured with aluminium were sourced from recycled aluminium material.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] The benefit with respect to emissions of carbon dioxide depends in part on the type of energy used.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Electrolysis can be done using electricity from non-fossil-fuel sources, such as nuclear, geothermal, hydroelectric, or solar.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Aluminium production is attracted to sources of cheap electricity.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Canada, Brazil, Norway, and Venezuela have 61 to 99% hydroelectric power and are major aluminium producers.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] However the anodes widely used in the Hall–Héroult process are made of carbon and are consumed during aluminium production, generating large quantities of carbon dioxide, regardless of electricity source.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Efforts are underway to eliminate the need for carbon anodes.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] The use of recycled aluminium also decreases the need for mining and refining bauxite.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] The vast amount of aluminium used means that even small percentage losses are large expenses, so the flow of material is well monitored and accounted for financial reasons.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Efficient production and recycling benefits the environment as well.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Because many countries continue to rely on coal-generated electricity for aluminium production, the aluminium industry contributes to 2% of global greenhouse gas emissions, around 1.1 billion tons of carbon dioxide.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Many countries now seek to decarbonize aluminium not only as it is the second most used metal in the world, but also because it would heavily address the total greenhouse gas emissions in an effort to slow climate change.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] As one of the most recyclable –and recycled– materials in use today, aluminium can be virtually infinitely recycled.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Since recycled aluminium takes 5% of the energy used to make new aluminium, around 75% of aluminium manufactured continues to be in use today.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] According to the Aluminium Association, in industrial markets such as automotive and building, aluminium is recycled at rates of up to 90%.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Since 1991, greenhouse gas emissions from aluminium cans have dropped about 40%, similar to energy demand levels.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] This can be attributed to a reduction in the carbon intensity of primary aluminium production, improving the efficacy of manufacturing operations, and lighter cans.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] While primary aluminium only accounts for 26.6% of the can, it makes up the major source of the can's carbon footprint.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] For example, as of 2020, 86% of China's aluminium production relies mostly on coal-generated electricity.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] On the other hand, Canada sources roughly 90% of its primary aluminium production using hydroelectric power, considering it to be the most sustainable in the world.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Aluminium and its applications are wide and numerous–from defense construction and electrical transmission to playing a key role in emission-reducing goods (electric vehicles and solar panels).
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] As such, countries have begun to decarbonize aluminium to combat global climate change.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Aluminium recycling has several economic benefits when done properly.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] In fact, the Environmental Protection Agency considers recycling a "critical" part of the United States economy, contributing to tax revenue, wages, and job creation.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] By facilitating scrap handling and improving its efficiency – from "end of life" scrap to repurposing scrap throughout the production stage ("in-house" scrap) – aluminium recycling helps in achieving the goals of a circular economy.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] This type of economy focuses on minimizing the extraction of natural resources, leading to a reduction of consumer and industrial waste.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] A few examples of countries that have adopted the shift to a circular economy include the European Union, Finland, France, Slovenia, Italy, Germany, and the Netherlands.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] A study conducted in the United States found several ways that aluminium recycling has proven to have economic benefits.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] The process increased the wages of waste management and the recycling industry from $2.1 billion to $5 billion, created more than 100,000 jobs in the United States economy, and produced $1.6 billion in material sales.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] It also saves enough energy to power 1.5 million homes per year, and keeps more than 1 million tons of waste out of landfills every year.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] According to 2020 data from the International Aluminium Institute, the global recycling efficiency rate is 76%.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Around 75% of the almost 1.5 billion tonnes of aluminium ever produced is still in productive use today.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Brazil recycles 98.2% of its aluminium can production, equivalent to 14.7 billion beverage cans per year, ranking first in the world, more than Japan's 82.5% recovery rate.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Brazil has topped the aluminium can recycling charts eight years in a row.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Aside from recycled aluminium beverage cans, the majority of recycled aluminium comes in a mixture of different alloys.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Those alloys generally have high percentages of silicon (Si) and require additional refinement during the shredding, sorting, and refining process to reduce impurities.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Due to the levels of impurities found after refinement, the applications of recycled aluminium alloys are limited to castings and extrusions.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] The aerospace industry often restrict impurity levels of Si and Fe in alloys to a 0.40% maximum.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Controlling the appearance of these elements is increasingly difficult the more often the metal has been recycled and require higher cost operations for the alloys to meet performance requirements.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] White dross, a residue from primary aluminium production and secondary recycling operations, usually classified as waste, still contains useful quantities of aluminium which can be extracted industrially.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] It reacts with water, releasing a mixture of gases (including, among others, hydrogen, acetylene, and ammonia) which spontaneously ignites on contact with air; contact with damp air results in the release of copious quantities of ammonia gas.
[src:ship-breaking/aluminium-recycling] Despite these difficulties, however, the waste has found use as a filler in asphalt and concrete.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In 2012, roughly 1,250 ocean ships were broken down, and their average age was 26 years.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In 2013, the world total of demolished ships amounted to 29,052,000 tonnes, 92% of which were demolished in Asia.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] As of January 2020, Alang Ship Breaking Yard in India has the largest global share at 30%, followed by Chittagong Ship Breaking Yard in Bangladesh and Gadani Ship Breaking Yard in Pakistan.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The largest sources of ships are China, Greece, and Germany, although there is greater variation in the sources of carriers versus their disposal.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The shipbreaking yards of India, Bangladesh, China and Pakistan employ 225,000 workers as well as providing many indirect jobs.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In Bangladesh, the recycled steel covers 20% of the country's needs, and in India, it is almost 10%.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] As an alternative to ship breaking, ships may be sunk to create artificial reefs after legally mandated removal of hazardous materials (though this does not recycle any materials), or sunk in deep ocean waters.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Storage is a viable temporary option, whether on land or afloat, though most ships will eventually be scrapped; some will be sunk, or alternatively be retained and preserved as museum ships.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Wooden-hulled ships were simply set on fire or "conveniently sunk".
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In Tudor times (1485–1603), ships were dismantled and the timber reused.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] This procedure was no longer applicable with the advent of metal-hulled boats in the 19th century.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In 1880, Denny Brothers of Dumbarton used forgings made from scrap maritime steel in their shipbuilding.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Many other nations began to purchase British ships for scrap by the late 19th century, including Germany, Italy, the Netherlands and Japan.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The Italian industry started in 1892, and the Japanese industry after the passing of an 1896 law to subsidise native shipbuilding.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] After suffering damage or disaster, liner operators did not want the name of a broken ship to tarnish the brand of their passenger services.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Many Victorian ships made their final voyages with the final letter of their name chipped off.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In the 1930s, it became cheaper to "beach" a boat by running her ashore—as opposed to using a dry dock.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The ship would have to weigh as little as possible and would run ashore at full speed.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Dismantling operations required a 10-foot (3 m) rise of tide and close proximity to a steelworks.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Electric shears, a wrecking ball and oxyacetylene torches were used.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The technique of the time closely resembles that used in developing countries as of 2020.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Ward Ltd., one of the largest breakers in the United Kingdom in the 1930s, would recondition and sell all furniture and machinery.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Many historical artifacts were sold at public auctions: the Cunarder RMS *Mauretania*, sold as scrap for £78,000, received high bids for her fittings worldwide.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] However, any weapons and military information, even if obsolete, were carefully removed by Navy personnel before turning over the ship for scrapping.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In 2020, as the COVID-19 pandemic crippled the cruise ship trade, cruise vessels began to appear more frequently in shipbreaking facilities.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Until the late 20th century, the majority of ship breaking activity took place in the port cities of industrialized countries such as the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] As of 2020, those dismantlers that still remain in the United States work primarily on government-surplus vessels.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Starting in the mid-20th century, East Asian countries with lower labour costs began to dominate ship breaking.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] As labour costs rose, centres of the shipbreaking industry moved—initially from countries such as Japan and Hong Kong, to Korea and Taiwan and then to China.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] At the time, Bangladesh had no capacity at all.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] However, the sector is volatile and fluctuates wildly, and Taiwan processed just two ships 13 years later as wages across East Asia rose.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] For comparison, depending on their profession, ship-breakers in Kaohsiung earned from NT$40 (day labourer) to NT$180 (torch operator) per day in 1973.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In 1960, after a severe cyclone, the Greek ship *M D Alpine* was stranded on the shores of Sitakunda, Chittagong (then part of East Pakistan).
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] It could not be refloated and so remained there for several years.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In 1965, the Chittagong Steel House bought the ship and had it scrapped.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] It took years to scrap the vessel, but the work gave birth to the industry in Bangladesh.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Until 1980, the Gadani Ship Breaking Yard of Pakistan was the largest shipbreaking yard in the world.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Tightening environmental regulations resulted in increased hazardous waste disposal costs in industrialised countries in the 1980s, causing the export of retired ships to lower-income areas, chiefly in South Asia.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] This, in turn, created a far worse environmental problem, subsequently leading to the Basel Convention of 1989.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In 2004, a Basel Convention decision officially classified old ships as "toxic waste", preventing them from leaving a country without the permission of the importing state.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] This has led to a resurgence of recycling in environmentally compliant locations in developed countries, especially in former shipbuilding yards.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] On 31 December 2005, the French Navy's *Clemenceau* left Toulon to be dismantled at the Alang Ship Breaking Yard, India—despite protests over improper disposal capabilities and facilities for the toxic wastes.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] On 6 January 2006, the Supreme Court of India temporarily denied access to Alang, and the French *Conseil d'État* ordered *Clemenceau* to return to French waters.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Able UK in Hartlepool received a new disassembly contract to use accepted practices in scrapping the ship.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The dismantling started on 18 November 2009 and the breakup was completed by the end of 2010; the event was considered a turning point in the treatment of redundant vessels.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Europe and the United States have had a resurgence in ship scrapping since the 1990s.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In 2009, the Bangladesh Environmental Lawyers Association won a legal case prohibiting all substandard ship breaking.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] For 14 months, the industry could not import ships and thousands of jobs were lost before the ban was annulled.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] That same year, the global recession and lower demand for goods led to an increase in the supply of ships for decommissioning.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The rate of scrapping is inversely correlated to the freight price, which collapsed in 2009.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The decommissioning process is entirely different in developed countries than it is in developing countries.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In both cases, ship-breakers bid for the ship, and the highest bidder wins the contract.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The ship-breaker then acquires the vessel from the international broker who deals in outdated ships.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The price paid is approximately $400 per tonne; regions with more lax environmental legislation typically can offer higher prices.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] For the industry in Bangladesh, 69% of revenue is spent on purchasing vessels; only 2% is labour costs.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The ship is taken to the decommissioning location either under its own power or with the use of tugs.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In developing countries, chiefly the Indian subcontinent, ships are run ashore on gently sloping sand tidal beaches at high tide so that they can be accessed for disassembly.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In the beaching method, no external source of energy is used to pull the ship, as opposed to the dry dock method of ship recycling where a ship is floated into the dry dock using a substantial amount of energy.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] However, maneuvering a large ship onto a beach at high speed takes skill and daring even for a specialist captain, and is not always successful.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Next, the anchor is dropped to steady the ship and the engine is shut down.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] It takes 50 labourers about three months to break down a normal-sized cargo vessel of about 40,000 tonnes.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Before the decommissioning begins, various clearances and permissions are obtained from regulatory, pollution and customs authorities after a thorough inspection is conducted by them.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The ship recycling process then begins with the draining of fuel, hydraulic fluid, coolant, lubricating oils and firefighting liquid, which may be disposed of or sold to the trade.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Any reusable fixtures are sold to the trade.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Any kind of waste such as plastic, garbage, or oily sand is sent to waste treatment facilities, like the Common Hazardous Waste Treatment Storage Disposal Facility (CHW-TSDF) set up by the Gujarat Maritime Board in Alang.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Any usable oil is sent to government-authorized refineries where used oil is chemically treated.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The next steps entail recovering unused and partially spent materials, disposal of bilge water, recovering and obtaining reusable materials, and safe disposal of biohazardous materials like asbestos and glass wool.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Each of these materials are inspected and sent to regulated waste treatment facilities or to buyers for further use and processing.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In developed countries, the dismantling process mirrors the technical guidelines for the environmentally sound management of the full and partial dismantling of ships, published by the Basel Convention in 2003.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Recycling rates of 98% can be achieved in these facilities.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Prior to dismantling, an inventory of dangerous substances is compiled.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] All hazardous materials and liquids, such as bilge water, are removed before disassembly.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Holes are bored for ventilation and all flammable vapours are extracted.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Vessels are initially taken to a dry dock or a pier, although a dry dock is considered more environmentally friendly because all spillage is contained and can easily be cleaned up.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Floating is, however, cheaper than a dry dock.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Stormwater discharge facilities will stop an overflow of toxic liquid into the waterways.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The carrier is then secured to ensure its stability.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Often, the propeller is removed beforehand to allow the watercraft to be moved into shallower water.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Anything of value, such as spare parts and electronic equipment, is sold for reuse, although labour costs mean that low-value items are not economical to sell.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The Basel Convention demands that all yards separate hazardous and non-hazardous waste and have appropriate storage units, and this must be done before the hull is cut up.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Asbestos, found in the engine room, is isolated and stored in custom-made plastic wrapping prior to being placed in secure steel containers, which are then landfilled.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Many hazardous wastes can be recycled into new products.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Examples include lead–acid batteries or electronic circuit boards.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Another commonly used treatment is cement-based solidification and stabilization.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Cement kilns are used because they can treat a range of hazardous wastes by improving physical characteristics and decreasing the toxicity and transmission of contaminants.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Hazardous waste may also be "destroyed" by incinerating it at a high temperature; flammable wastes can sometimes be burned as energy sources.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Some hazardous waste types may be eliminated using pyrolysis in a high-temperature electrical arc, in inert conditions to avoid combustion.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] This treatment method may be preferable to high-temperature incineration in some circumstances such as in the destruction of concentrated organic waste types, including PCBs, pesticides, and other persistent organic pollutants.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Dangerous chemicals can also be permanently stored in landfills as long as leaching is prevented.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Valuable metals, such as copper or aluminum in electric cable, that are mixed with other materials may be recovered by the use of shredders and separators in the same fashion as e-waste recycling.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The shredders cut the electronics into metallic and non-metallic pieces.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Metals are extracted using magnetic separators, air flotation separator columns, shaker tables, or eddy currents.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Plastic almost always contains regulated hazardous waste (e.g., asbestos, PCBs, hydrocarbons) and cannot be melted down.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Large objects, such as engine parts, are extracted and sold as they become accessible.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The hull is cut into 300-tonne sections, starting with the upper deck and working slowly downwards.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] While oxyacetylene gas torches are most commonly used, detonation charges can quickly remove large sections of the hull.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] These sections are transported to an electric arc furnace to be melted down into new ferrous products, though toxic paint must be stripped prior to heating.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] At Kaohsiung in the late 1960s and '70s, ships to be scrapped were tied up at berths in Dah Jen and Dah Lin Pu, at the southern end of Kaohsiung Harbor.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] There were a total of 24 breaking berths at Kaohsiung; each berth was rented by the scrapper from the Port Authority at a nominal rate of NT$7 per square foot per month, and up to 18,000 square feet (1,700 m2) could be rented surrounding a 300-foot-long (91 m) berth at a time.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] A typical 5,000-ton ship could be broken up in 25 to 30 days.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The process began with "cleaning", a process in which subcontractors would come on board the ship to strip it of loose and flammable items, which were often resold in second-hand shops.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] After that, the cutting crews would start to dismantle the hull, stern first; large sections were cut off the ship and moved via cranes and rigging taken from previously scrapped ships.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Because the scrapping at Kaohsiung was done at the docks, scrap metal was placed on trucks waiting to transport it to Kaohsiung's mills.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The Basel Convention on the Control of Trans-boundary Movements of Hazardous Wastes and Their Disposal of 1989 was the first convention to environmentally govern the shipbreaking industry.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] It has been ratified by 187 countries, including India and Bangladesh.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] It controls the international movement of hazardous wastes and for their environmentally sound management mainly through consent for the shipment between the authorities of the country exporting the hazardous wastes with the authorities of the importing country.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Though the Basel Convention has notably reduced illegal exports of hazardous wastes to countries that are unable to process and dispose of them in an environmentally sound manner, it has failed to define the minimum standards of recycling soundly.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] It also completely ignores important aspects such as workers' safety and falls short in overcoming bureaucratic barriers when it comes to communication between exporting and importing countries.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Furthermore, the decision to scrap a ship is often made in international waters, where the convention has no jurisdiction.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The "Ban Amendment" to the Basel Convention was adopted in March 1994, prohibiting the export of hazardous wastes from OECD countries to non-OECD countries.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The Amendment would enter into force 90 days after it has been ratified by at least three-quarters of the 87 countries that were Parties to the Convention at the time it was adopted.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Croatia deposited the 66th ratification in September 2019, and the Ban Amendment entered into force 25 years after adoption on December 5, 2019.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] However, the European Union had already enacted the Ban Amendment unilaterally through the European Waste Shipment Regulation, which incorporated the Basel Convention and the Ban Amendment into European Union law in February 1993.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] When the European Commission attempted to apply the WSR to end-of-life ships, it encountered numerous obstacles and evasion.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] This is because, in enforcing the Ban Amendment, the European Waste WSR considers it illegal to recycle any ship that has started its last voyage from a European Union port in Bangladesh, China, India, or Pakistan, regardless of the flag the ship flies.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] These four non-OECD countries have consistently recycled around 95% of the world's tonnage.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In fact, according to a study conducted by the European Commission in 2011, at least 91% of ships covered by the WSR disobeyed or circumvented its requirements.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The European Commission admitted publicly that enforcing its own Waste Shipment Regulation to recycle ships had not been successful.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The commission, unable to wait for the Hong Kong Convention (HKC) to take effect, began developing new legislation to regulate the recycling of European-flagged ships.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] This led the European Commission in 2012 to propose the development of a new European Regulation on Ship Recycling.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Thus, the Hong Kong Convention came into existence.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In essence, the Convention aims to ensure that ships, when being recycled after reaching the end of their operational lives, do not pose any unnecessary risks to human health, safety and the environment.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] 3. the establishment of an appropriate enforcement mechanism for ship recycling (certification/reporting requirements).
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] With much more sound standards of ship recycling, easier implementation and better supervision, the Hong Kong Convention was finally adopted in 2009.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The conditions for its entry into force were fulfilled in 2023, and the Convention entered into force on 25 June 2025.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] 3. the combined maximum annual ship recycling volume of the States during the preceding 10 years to constitute not less than 3 percent of the gross tonnage of the combined merchant shipping of the same States.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] As of 2 April 2023, 20 countries have acceded to the HKC, making up 30.16% of the world's merchant shipping by gross tonnage, with a combined maximum annual ship recycling volume of the States at 2.6 % of the gross tonnage of the combined merchant shipping of the same States.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Subsequent accessions increased both figures beyond the required thresholds, enabling the Convention to enter into force on 25 June 2025.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Nearly 110 of India's 120 operational ship recycling yards have achieved Statements of Compliance (SoC) with the Hong Kong Convention by various IACS class societies—including ClassNK, IRClass, Lloyd's Register and RINA.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In Bangladesh, 17 ship recycling yards have now achieved Statements of Compliance with the Hong Kong Convention.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The work on the EU's Ship Recycling Regulation (SRR) was started in 2013, after the adoption of the requirements from the Hong Kong International Convention for the safe and environmentally sound recycling of ships (HKC).
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Europeans own around 40% of the world fleet, around 15,000 ships.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Among these, around 10,000 fly an EU Member State flag, but only 7% of the EU-flagged ships are dismantled in the EU territory, and the rest are mostly dismantled in South Asia.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] After the financial crisis in the early 2010s, many shipowners ended up with an unexpected overcapacity of ships, and were selling off their vessels.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The phasing out of single-hull oil tankers also provided a rush to change out one's fleet.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The EU's new FuelEU maritime initiative is also incentivising decarbonization of the maritime sector, which requires ships to sail on new renewables or less polluting fuels.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] This implies that the EU fleet already has and will undergo major changes and renewals in the coming years, thus leading to many ships being outdated or phased out, many being concerned for the end-of-life handling of these older ships.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The SRR aims to address the environmental and health hazards associated with ship dismantling by setting high standards for EU-flagged vessels at the end of their operational lives.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] One of the key components developed by the EU is the European List of Approved Ship Recycling Facilities, identifying the approved ports for all EU-flagged ships to be recycled.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] For a ship recycling yard to be included in the list, the facilities must comply with strict environmental and worker safety standards, reducing toxic waste release and promoting safe dismantling practices.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Member States report to the Commission on which facilities in their territory that comply to the requirements, and thereby are included on the list.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Shipyards outside the EU can also be included on the European List but must apply to the Commission with proof of the yard's standards.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] To be included on the European List, ship recycling facilities must adhere to specific requirements set by the EU and aligned with the Hong Kong Convention and other international guidelines.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Facilities need authorization, robust structural and operational standards, environmental safety protocols, and measures for monitoring health and safety risks to workers and nearby populations.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] This includes handling hazardous materials on impermeable surfaces, training workers and provide them with protective equipment, implementing emergency plans, and recording incidents.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Operators must also submit recycling plans and completion reports, ensuring full compliance and minimizing environmental and health impacts during ship recycling activities.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] As of November 2024, it contains 45 shipyards.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Because the list works as a guarantee for a yard's safety and validity, shipyards can both be removed and added to the list if they cease to comply with the regulation.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Additionally, to the list of approved facilities, the SRR also mandates each ship to hold an Inventory of Hazardous Materials (IHM), listing hazardous substances used in each ship's construction.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] "Hazardous material" refers to any material or substance which is liable to create hazards to human health and/or the environment.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] New installation of material such as asbestos and ozone-depleting substances are prohibited, and the occurrence of materials containing lead, mercury and radioactive substances, to name a few, are to be reported and restricted.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] This inventory, which must be maintained throughout the ship's life, helps guide shipyards and recyclers on safe waste management and reduces accidental environmental contamination.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The ships also report on the operationally generated waste, meaning wastewater and residues generated by the normal operation of ships.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] By EU standards, any EU ship going for dismantling, all new European ships, and third-country ships stopping in EU ports need to have an inventory of hazardous materials on board.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] This list, as of 27 July 2023, contains 48 ship recycling facilities, including 38 yards in Europe (EU, Norway and UK), nine yards in Turkey and one yard in the USA.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Several yards on the European List are also capable of recycling large vessels.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The list excluded some of the most major ship recycling yards in India and Bangladesh, which have achieved SoCs with the HKC in various class societies.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] This exclusion has led to many shipowners changing the flag of their vessel before recycling or sell the ship to cash buyers, to evade the regulations.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Excluded countries strive towards bringing the HKC into force as the universal regulation, arguing that it would be irrational if international shipping were regulated by multiple and competing standards.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The EU Ship Recycling Regulation (EUSRR) faces practical issues that limit its global impact.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Industry groups, including the European Community Shipowners' Associations (ECSA), have pointed out that several Indian ship recycling yards meet or exceed international standards but remain excluded from the European List.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The European Union has audited some of these yards yet withheld approval for reasons outside the control of the yard operators.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Examples include the absence of a trauma centre and downstream waste management facilities of EU standard within immediate proximity.The Gujarat Maritime Board has already allocated funding to build a trauma centre in Alang, but these investments have not changed the approval outcome.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The method of beaching ships is another area of concern.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] While the EUSRR does not explicitly prohibit beaching, the lack of approvals for yards using this method suggests an indirect disqualification.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Technical assessments show that when managed with strict environmental and safety controls, beaching can achieve safe and environmentally sound recycling comparable to alternative methods.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Economic data further illustrates the challenge.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Unskilled labour wages in South Asia range from 4 to 6 US dollars per day.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In Turkey, wages are about 16 to 17 US dollars per day.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] For a 10,000 light displacement tonnage (LDT) vessel requiring four months of recycling and about 100 workers, the wage difference adds about 144,000 US dollars or roughly 15 US dollars per LDT.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Hazardous waste disposal is also less costly in India.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Disposal of asbestos costs about 300 US dollars per ton in India compared to 800 US dollars per ton in Turkey.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Paint chip disposal costs about 200 US dollars per ton in India compared to 500 US dollars per ton in Turkey.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] A typical recycling project can save about 150,000 US dollars in environmental and waste management costs when performed in India instead of Turkey.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The market value of recycled steel compounds the disparity.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Turkey and other EU-approved yards send most recovered ferrous material for melting, which generates lower domestic value compared to the direct reuse of steel plates common in South Asia.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] This reduces the price per LDT that EU-approved yards can offer.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Turkey often pays 90 to 160 US dollars less per LDT than South Asian yards, and some EU-listed yards pay 200 to 300 US dollars less.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Evidence also shows that higher costs do not always equate to better environmental results.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] A 2012 study reported heavy metal contamination at levels above prescribed limits in the Aliağa ship recycling zone in Turkey.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] This raises questions about whether EUSRR requirements guarantee superior environmental outcomes.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Experts recommend that the EU consider a bilateral agreement with India to address these issues and to reflect actual safety and environmental performance in its yard approvals.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Such an approach could strengthen global compliance and create a more balanced economic framework for ship recycling.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Seventy percent of ships are simply run ashore in developing countries for disassembly, where (particularly in older vessels) potentially toxic materials such as asbestos, lead, polychlorinated biphenyls and heavy metals along with lax industrial safety standards pose a danger for the workers.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Burns from explosions and fire, suffocation, mutilation from falling metal, cancer and disease from toxins are regular occurrences in the industry.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Asbestos was used heavily in ship construction until it was finally banned in most of the developed world in the mid-1980s.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Currently, the costs associated with removing asbestos, along with the potentially expensive insurance and health risks, have meant that shipbreaking in most developed countries is no longer economically viable.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Dangerous vapours and fumes from burning materials can be inhaled, and dusty asbestos-laden areas are commonplace.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Removing the metal for scrap can potentially cost more than the value of the scrap metal itself.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In the developing world, however, shipyards can operate without the risk of personal injury lawsuits or workers' health claims, meaning many of these shipyards may operate with high health risks.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Protective equipment is sometimes absent or inadequate.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The sandy beaches cannot sufficiently support the heavy equipment, which is thus prone to collapse.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Many are injured from explosions when flammable gas is not removed from fuel tanks.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In Bangladesh, a local watchdog group claims that, on average, one worker dies per week and one is injured per day.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The problem is caused by negligence from national governments, shipyard operators and former ship owners disregarding the Basel Convention.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] According to the Institute for Global Labour and Human Rights, workers who attempt to unionize are fired and then blacklisted.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The employees have no formal contract or any rights, and sleep in overcrowded hostels.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The authorities produce no comprehensive injury statistics, so the problem is underestimated.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Child labour is also widespread: 20% of Bangladesh's ship breaking workforce are below 15 years of age, mainly involved in cutting with gas torches.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] There is, however, an active ship-breaker's union in Mumbai, India (Mumbai Port Trust Dock and General Employees' Union) since 2003 with 15,000 members, which strikes to ensure fatality compensation.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] It has set up a sister branch in Alang, gaining paid holidays and safety equipment for workers since 2005.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] They hope to expand all along the South Asian coastline.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Even poor occupational safety record at Alang, the world's largest ship recycling destination, underlines the risks of the shipbreaking industry.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Poor worker safety has led to a number of accidents and dozens of workers' deaths at the Alang yards over the years.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] According the IndustriALL Global Union affiliate, Alang Sosiya Ship Recycling and General Workers' Association (ASSRGWA), between January 2009 and October 2012, at least 54 workers had died in work-related accidents at the Alang shipbreaking yards.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Besides worker unions, such frequent accidents due to poor safety standards at Alang have also attracted EU scrutiny.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In addition to this, GMB has also included regular medical examinations of workers exposed to biohazardous materials, provision of medical facilities at the Red Cross Hospital in Alang, mobile medical vans and health awareness programmes.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Several United Nations committees are increasing their coverage of ship-breakers' human rights.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] In 2006, the International Maritime Organisation developed legally binding global legislation which concerns vessel design, vessel recycling and the enforcement of regulation thereof and a 'Green Passport' scheme.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Watercraft must have an inventory of hazardous material before they are scrapped, and the facilities must meet health and safety requirements.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The International Labour Organization created a voluntary set of guidelines for occupational safety in 2003.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Nevertheless, Greenpeace found that even pre-existing mandatory regulation has had little noticeable effect for labourers, due to government corruption, yard owner secrecy and a lack of interest from countries who prioritise economic growth.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] There are also guards who look out for any reporters.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] To safeguard worker health, the report recommends that developed countries create a fund to support their families, certify carriers as 'gas-free' (i.e. safe for cutting) and to remove toxic materials in appropriate facilities before export.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] To supplement the international treaties, organisations such as the NGO Shipbreaking Platform, the Institute for Global Labour and Human Rights and ToxicsWatch Alliance are lobbying for improvements in the industry.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Ship recycling was once a major environmental and occupational health concern.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Many yards lacked strict controls and allowed hazardous materials to contaminate air, soil and water, creating risks for workers and local communities.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Environmental and worker safety groups such as Greenpeace and International Labour Organization (ILO) continue to monitor compliance.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Earlier assessments highlighted risks to mangroves, biodiversity and coastal stability.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Recent studies and international oversight indicate that certified yards in Bangladesh and India now operate under improved waste management and coastal protection measures in line with HKC requirements.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The Hong Kong International Convention for the Safe and Environmentally Sound Recycling of Ships, adopted in 2009 and entered into force on 25 June 2025, was designed to address these concerns on a global scale.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The Convention sets legally binding requirements for the design, construction, operation and preparation of ships so they can be recycled without endangering human health or the environment.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] It also requires ship recycling facilities to meet strict standards for hazardous waste handling, worker safety and environmental protection, and to obtain certification and provide detailed reporting.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The Basel Convention on the Control of Transboundary Movements of Hazardous Wastes and Their Disposal of 1989 has been ratified by 166 countries, including India and Bangladesh, and in 2004, end-of-life ships were subjected to its regulations.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] It aims to stop the transportation of dangerous substances to less-developed countries and mandate the use of regulated facilities.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The decision to scrap a ship is often made in international waters, beyond the Basel Convention's scope.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The European Union Ship Recycling Regulation, fully applicable since 2018 and under regular review, requires EU-flagged vessels to be dismantled in facilities listed on the European List of approved yards.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Under these rules, if a vessel has a European flag, it must be disposed of in a shipyard on an EU "green list".
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The facilities would have to show that they are compliant, and it would be regulated internationally in order to bypass corrupt local authorities.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] However, there is evidence of shipowners changing their vessel's flag to evade the regulations.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] China's scrap industry has vehemently protested against the proposed European regulations.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Although Chinese recycling businesses are less damaging than their South Asian counterparts, European and American ship-breakers comply with far more stringent legislation.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] The ship recycling industry also produces about 4.5 million tons of re-rollable steel per year.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] That comes up to nearly 2% of total steel produced in India, coming from a process that does not exploit natural resources and thereby saves nonrenewable natural resources and energy.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Recycling of one ton of scrap saves 1.1 tons of iron ore, 0.6–0.7 tons of coking coal and around 0.2–0.3 tons of fluxes.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Specific energy consumption for production of steel through BF-BOF (primary) and EAF& IF (secondary routes) is 14 MJ/kg and 11.7 MJ/kg, respectively.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Thus, it leads to savings in energy by 16–17%.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] It also reduces the water consumption and GHG emission by 40% and 58%, respectively.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] As of 2025, India remains one of the world's largest ship recycling centres, handling about 30 percent of global ship breaking by volume.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] India ratified the Hong Kong International Convention for the Safe and Environmentally Sound Recycling of Ships in 2019 through its *Recycling of Ships Act, 2019*, and the Convention entered into force on 25 June 2025.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] Nearly all active yards in Alang and other centres now operate with Statements of Compliance issued by internationally recognised classification societies, meeting Hong Kong Convention standards for worker safety, hazardous-waste management and environmental protection.
[src:ship-breaking/ship-breaking] These measures have positioned India to receive a growing share of end-of-life vessels from Europe, Japan, and other Hong Kong Convention Parties, supporting continued expansion of the country’s recycling revenue and capacity.
